WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.150 --> 00:00:01.260
- Is everything you're going to need

00:00:01.260 --> 00:00:03.780
to know about these astronauts coming home

00:00:03.780 --> 00:00:05.610
and the challenges they're going to face.

00:00:05.610 --> 00:00:08.700
My name's John Jake. I'm a
doctor of biomedical engineering

00:00:08.700 --> 00:00:13.560
and I have done extensive work
in bone density treatment,

00:00:13.560 --> 00:00:16.950
which is one of the key
challenges that those

00:00:16.950 --> 00:00:20.010
who leave the comfort of the gravity field

00:00:20.010 --> 00:00:22.830
that the earth provides have to deal with

00:00:22.830 --> 00:00:24.270
when they return earth.

00:00:24.270 --> 00:00:28.680
They're going to notice the
problems that have been added

00:00:28.680 --> 00:00:33.150
to the general physical challenges
based on poor digestion,

00:00:33.150 --> 00:00:36.030
like gravity is required
for proper digestion.

00:00:36.030 --> 00:00:39.540
So they've already been suffering from

00:00:39.540 --> 00:00:40.860
compromised digestion.

00:00:40.860 --> 00:00:45.150
No doubt they will have had
some shrinkage of their stomach

00:00:45.150 --> 00:00:47.520
and digestive system just

00:00:47.520 --> 00:00:49.110
because it's so difficult

00:00:49.110 --> 00:00:51.300
to digest food in a zero
gravity environment.

00:00:51.300 --> 00:00:52.980
They're accustomed to eating less

00:00:52.980 --> 00:00:54.780
and they're gonna need to eat more now

00:00:54.780 --> 00:00:56.130
that they're back on earth

00:00:56.130 --> 00:00:58.230
and can actually utilize that nutrition.

00:00:58.230 --> 00:00:59.820
They'll be lucky if they can even get

00:00:59.820 --> 00:01:00.960
to maintenance calories.

00:01:00.960 --> 00:01:03.690
Their, their digestive system
has been so compromised

00:01:03.690 --> 00:01:06.000
and they haven't been able to eat a lot.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:08.460
Gravity is required to really pull food

00:01:08.460 --> 00:01:10.560
through your digestive system.

00:01:10.560 --> 00:01:13.740
If it were me, it would be
an almost all protein diet.

00:01:13.740 --> 00:01:16.530
I would encourage nutrient dense.

00:01:16.530 --> 00:01:18.090
It would pretty much just be butter

00:01:18.090 --> 00:01:20.220
and steak would be the recommendation.

00:01:20.220 --> 00:01:21.930
The highest nutrient dense foods

00:01:21.930 --> 00:01:25.890
and as much strength exercise,
which would be relative

00:01:25.890 --> 00:01:27.210
to their level of conditioning.

00:01:27.210 --> 00:01:29.250
So day one, they're
probably gonna go to sleep.

00:01:29.250 --> 00:01:33.300
Day two, they're gonna do very
simple stuff like body weight

00:01:33.300 --> 00:01:36.420
squats, you know, sit to stands in a chair

00:01:36.420 --> 00:01:37.650
and they're just standing up.

00:01:37.650 --> 00:01:40.590
They haven't had to balance
themselves for a long time

00:01:40.590 --> 00:01:42.360
and that's, that's going to show

00:01:42.360 --> 00:01:44.370
and they're gonna feel
that just getting on

00:01:44.370 --> 00:01:46.230
and off the toilet is gonna be hard

00:01:46.230 --> 00:01:48.090
because it's, that's like a squat

00:01:48.090 --> 00:01:51.030
and they're weak, so they'll
have trouble getting on

00:01:51.030 --> 00:01:52.290
and off of it, but that's it.

00:01:52.290 --> 00:01:53.730
Then on top of that,

00:01:53.730 --> 00:01:56.550
because they have not had
mechanical loading going

00:01:56.550 --> 00:01:58.950
through their musculoskeletal
system, they're going

00:01:58.950 --> 00:02:02.430
to have a loss of bone
density that is noticed

00:02:02.430 --> 00:02:04.920
and a loss of muscle mass that is noticed

00:02:04.920 --> 00:02:06.900
and they're gonna have to begin training

00:02:06.900 --> 00:02:10.080
to treat those deficiencies very quickly

00:02:10.080 --> 00:02:11.820
because they're, they're
frail at this point.

00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:14.490
It'll probably take them
six months to a year

00:02:14.490 --> 00:02:16.980
to recover their strength and bone mass.

00:02:16.980 --> 00:02:19.560
Significant losses happen in zero gravity.

00:02:19.560 --> 00:02:21.480
Regular weightlifting just not that great.

00:02:21.480 --> 00:02:25.110
What we need is a weight
that changes as we move so

00:02:25.110 --> 00:02:26.610
that it accommodates our,

00:02:26.610 --> 00:02:30.480
our strength curve delivers a
much more exhausting stimulus,

00:02:30.480 --> 00:02:32.940
therefore guaranteeing muscular growth.

00:02:32.940 --> 00:02:37.380
If they train correctly in
the most efficient manner

00:02:37.380 --> 00:02:40.950
within probably the same amount
of time that they were gone,

00:02:40.950 --> 00:02:42.510
if they dedicate that to training,

00:02:42.510 --> 00:02:45.450
they could restore all
the damage that was done

00:02:45.450 --> 00:02:47.880
by the zero gravity
environment they would need

00:02:47.880 --> 00:02:50.220
to be doing four days a week.

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:51.840
Because you do need some time to recover

00:02:51.840 --> 00:02:53.310
between exercise stimuli.

00:02:53.310 --> 00:02:57.510
Activities of daily living
would probably be challenging

00:02:57.510 --> 00:03:00.250
for most people in this situation.

00:03:00.250 --> 00:03:03.460
However, you could put
astronauts in the same category

00:03:03.460 --> 00:03:06.130
as Navy Seals in the amount of training

00:03:06.130 --> 00:03:07.600
and discipline that they have.

00:03:07.600 --> 00:03:10.510
So they're well aware of
what they signed up for.

00:03:10.510 --> 00:03:12.520
They know exactly what they need to do

00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:15.400
and they're probably not
even gonna complain about it.

00:03:15.400 --> 00:03:18.430
Ultimately. I have
heard astronauts tell me

00:03:18.430 --> 00:03:22.300
that like the weight of a a
pencil feels very strange in

00:03:22.300 --> 00:03:24.610
their hand because everything
they've grabbed a hold

00:03:24.610 --> 00:03:28.180
of had no weight to it
for the last few months.

00:03:28.180 --> 00:03:31.810
So just simple activities
seem either challenging

00:03:31.810 --> 00:03:34.570
or oddly difficult or it feels strange.

00:03:34.570 --> 00:03:36.520
But again, these are NASA astronauts.

00:03:36.520 --> 00:03:39.880
They're ready for this. When
astronauts are recruited,

00:03:39.880 --> 00:03:43.630
they pick the ones who they
know have the mental fortitude

00:03:43.630 --> 00:03:47.230
to handle being stranded
in space for a few months.

00:03:47.230 --> 00:03:50.200
These individuals,
they're problem solvers.

00:03:50.200 --> 00:03:54.520
They don't panic, they think
their way through everything.

00:03:54.520 --> 00:03:57.370
Now the chances of one of
them having a, a mental

00:03:57.370 --> 00:03:59.710
or emotional breakdown
is still significant

00:03:59.710 --> 00:04:01.420
because it's very difficult
what they went through.

00:04:01.420 --> 00:04:05.710
But they are so highly trained
that it's rare where any

00:04:05.710 --> 00:04:09.195
of them have any mental breakdown or

00:04:09.195 --> 00:04:10.570
or are just in distress.

00:04:10.570 --> 00:04:13.810
This is something NASA has
done exceptionally well.

00:04:13.810 --> 00:04:15.670
They really know how to pick the people

00:04:15.670 --> 00:04:17.200
and then they train them so

00:04:17.200 --> 00:04:20.500
that they don't ever self-sabotage

00:04:20.500 --> 00:04:22.270
because in a situation like that,

00:04:22.270 --> 00:04:23.860
you are your own worst enemy.

00:04:23.860 --> 00:04:26.470
You are the one who's gonna
do something in a panic

00:04:26.470 --> 00:04:30.310
that might be a mistake and
they're trained not to do that.

00:04:30.310 --> 00:04:32.920
They think everything through
radiation is an issue.

00:04:32.920 --> 00:04:36.760
Our atmosphere blocks a significant
portion of the radiation

00:04:36.760 --> 00:04:40.870
that is apparent in just
the part of outer space

00:04:40.870 --> 00:04:42.040
that is very close to earth.

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:46.360
So more exposure than
you would get in a couple

00:04:46.360 --> 00:04:47.830
of x-rays at the dentist.

00:04:47.830 --> 00:04:50.860
But the proximity to the sun tends to be

00:04:50.860 --> 00:04:52.930
where the real radiation concerns are.

00:04:52.930 --> 00:04:55.090
So they're not gonna be
like damaged for life

00:04:55.090 --> 00:04:56.770
because of radiation exposure.

00:04:56.770 --> 00:04:59.740
There's such high anxiety in space like,

00:04:59.740 --> 00:05:02.410
are we gonna even make it
home once they get home?

00:05:02.410 --> 00:05:04.270
It's just kind of a collapse.

00:05:04.270 --> 00:05:06.100
You're fighting to stay alive one day

00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:08.530
and then the next day you
don't even know your purpose.

00:05:08.530 --> 00:05:10.390
It's depressing. I mean, ironically,

00:05:10.390 --> 00:05:11.710
it's like your life has been saved.

00:05:11.710 --> 00:05:12.730
You're back here on earth.

00:05:12.730 --> 00:05:13.810
But they always feel that way

00:05:13.810 --> 00:05:15.190
'cause they're fighting
for their life one day

00:05:15.190 --> 00:05:16.525
and that hurts.

